{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_myrtle_ver01/data/56022775/00541313400/1949062701/0135.xml":{"full_text":"Official Weekly Publication\nTrainman News\nBrotherhood of Railroad Trainmen\nA. F. Whitney, President\nW. P. Kennedy, General Secretary and Treasurer\nPublished weekly at Cleveland, Ohio\nEditorial Office: 1244 Standard Building, Cleveland 13, Ohio\nPOSTMASTER: Send Forms 3578 or 3579 to Business Office\n1348 Standard Bldg., Cleveland 13, Ohio\nAll communications or news items for publication in TRAINMAN\nNEWS must be in the office of the Editor by 5 P. M. of Tuesday of\nthe week for which publication is intended. Snapshots are not suit\nable for reproduction, but glossy prints (not smaller than 5x7)\nare welcome and should reach the Editor\u2019s office not later than 9\nA. M. Tuesday.\nSubscription rate $1.00 per year: Individual copies 10 cents\nNo commercial advertising accepted.\nEntered as second class matter at the post office at Cleveland, Ohio\nIrvin S. Lippe, Editor\nAssociates: George H. Hennemuth II, Louis E. Corsi\nVol. .3. No. 26\n\"8027\nJune 27,1949\nWhen People Know\n(Guest editorial from The Progressive)\nThe American Medical Association\u2019s multi-million-dollar\noffensive against President Truman\u2019s national health insur\nance program is rapidly taking form as the most brazen\nattempt to flood the nation with false and misleading propa\nganda since the heyday of the old utility mob.\nWhitaker Baxter, the public relations firm whose tac\ntics and strategy Nathan Robertson analyzed for readers of\nthe progressive in the May issue, have now unveiled more of\nthe program by which their client, the AMA, hopes to crush\nthe move to give the people of the United States the protec\ntion of health insurance.\nStep No. 1 is national application of the California experi\nence. In that state Whitaker Baxter were hired to beat\nGovernor Warren\u2019s state health insurance program. They\nbought a minimum of 100 column inches in each of 700 news\npapers and then proceeded to collect in return free publicity\n\u201cfar beyond anything we expected.\u201d At a national conference\nof state medical societies in Chicago recently, the publicity\nfirm proclaimed the national strategy to be this:\n\n\u201cWe intend to work with the great newspapers and na\ntional magazines to get them to do special jobs and that work\nis already well started. Once an article has been printed, re\nprints will be placed in the hands of key people to be dis\ntributed thruout the country.\u201d\nStep No. 2 is to \u201clocate the principal physician of every\ncongressman and every U. S. senator and have him\u2014the\nphysician\u2014send a personal letter to his patient\u2014the con\ngressman\u2014telling him of the danger of socialized medicine.\u201d\nThis crude exploitation of physician-patient relationship\nfor political lobbying purposes does not end there, for Step No.\n3 would make every doctor\u2019s office, by loading it with Whit\naker Baxter leaflets and photographs, a precinct headquar\nters.\nWhile doctors would thus be armed with hand-outs pre\npared by the AMA's public relations counselors, they would be\ndiscouraged from using their own minds in public. Whitaker\nBaxter have now directed physicians to avoid \u201ctoo many\u201d\ndebates on the health insurance issue.\nIt is a heartening tribute to the horse sense of the Amer\nican people that they use more than the prescribed grain of\nsalt when confronted with AMA propaganda\u2014propaganda, by\nthe way, which the British Medical Association has twice been\nobliged to denounce as \u201cgross distortion\u201d as applied to the\nBritish medical program.\nThe AMERICAN DRUGGIST recently published the results of\ntwo significant polls\u2014both suppressed by the press which is\n\u201cdoing special jobs\u201d for the AMA. Now, the AMERICAN\nDRUGGIST is opposed to national health insurance. It hired a\npoll-taking firm which is also opposed to the President\u2019s pro\ngram. The firm polled 1,500 presidents and program chair\nmen of citizens\u2019 organizations with a \"combined membership\nof 40 million. The results:\nOf those who took a position, 67 per cent said they fa\nvored national health insurance. Of \u201cthose with knowledge of\nthe Truman program,\u201d 79 per cent favored it.\nThe AMERICAN DRUGGIST also took a postcard poll of 2,500\npharmacists. The results showed that 17 per cent favored\ncompulsory health insurance\u2014double the number of three\nyears ago. And here too, significantly, as the magazine pointed\nout with alarm, \u201cThe more the retail druggist knows about\nthe Truman proposal, the more likely he is to favor it.\u201d\nThe results of these polls seem to us extraordinarily im\npressive. What strikes us as most hopeful in the findings of a\nhostile journal is the fact that when people know the facts\u2014\nwhen they know that the President\u2019s program does not mean\nsocialized medicine; when they know that it leaves physicians\nfree to choose or reject patients, as they do now, or free to\ndecline to come under the program altogether; when they\nknow that it retains for patients complete freedom of choice\nof a physician; when they know it will mean a program of\nvastly expanded hospital construction, more medical schools\nand doctors, far more equitable distribution of medical facili\nties, and low-cost insurance protection\u2014when they know\nwhat is in the program, they support it by overwhelming\nmajorities.\nX\nCondemned to Die?\n37\n*1\nAx\n\nAMERICAN\nMEDICAL\nF\"ND TO F\\GHT\nAAERUATE PUBLC\n\"ALTH LEGISLATION\nHaute\nPRAWN FoR\nTKAJNMjfyN\nWun NIonev\u2019s Worth\nBy MARY SHERIDAN\nTrainman News Staff Writer\nGood news for prospective buyers keep\ning an eye on used car lots is the Federal\nTrade Commission\u2019s announcement of a con\nference Sept. 15 to work out ways of end\ning \u201cconcealed overcharges\u201d in the sale and\nfinancing of automobiles.\nAutomobile dealers, financing companies,\nand manufacturers will be called to the con\nference, where FTC will try to establish a\nplan under which all car buyers will get an\nitemized breakdown of items making up the\ntotal price and a separate listing of financ\ning and insurance charges.\nIn calling the conference, the FTC said,\n\u201cIt is claimed that the concealment of the\nnature, size, and extent of the overcharge\nin the monthly payments, by lumping\nfinance charges and insurance, or otherwise,\nin the contract constitutes a concealment of\nmaterial fact.\u201d That is a formal way of say\ning that buyers have been gypped by high\ninterest charges and \u201cincidentals\u201d in time\npayments on used cars.\nThe FTC conference is very timely not\nonly because of buyers\u2019 complaints but be\nsome surveys indicate that more\ncause\npeople, compared to 1947 or early 1948, plan\nto buy used cars this year. In my town al\nmost every filling station has a used car or\ntwo for sale, and the bigger used car lots\nare crowded with everything from 1930\nmodels to town and country convertibles.\nStill only in the rumor stage is the gossip\nthat car prices will come down in July and\ncome down even more after Labor Day. If\nyou can wait, there is a better than even\nchance of getting a car for less within three\nmonths.\nWhether you buy a new or used car, be\nwarned by the complaints which have\nprompted FTC\u2019s conference on used car\nsales and financing. Finance it thru your\ncredit union or co-op insurance or bank.\nHave someone who knows contracts read\nyours to be sure it is clear how much and\nfor what the various charges are.\n\nEvery week we hear more talk about a\nrecession, possible depression, and rumb\nlings or layoffs. Along with this talk there\nare business complaints that people aren\u2019t\nbuying major appliances. A much more op\ntimistic report, contradicting the gloom in\nsome circles about the next year or two, is\nthe survey made for the Federal Reserve\nBoard by the Institute for Social Research\nof the University of Michigan.\nOn the basis of a consumer poll made be\ntween Jan. 5 and March 5, more consumers\nthan in 1948 said that they planned to buy\ncars, moderately priced houses, and tele\nvision sets during 1949. Consumers indi\ncated that the price drops early this year\nmeant better times, not a depression.\nThe institute poll, of course, covered only\na few thousands of consumers. Since there\nare millions of consumers, there is a chance\nthat the poll could be wrong\u2014and we are\nall a bit skeptical of polls these days. How\never, the institute\u2019s poll makers insist their\ntesting method is more careful than most\npolitical polls.\nAmong the poll findings which interested\nme most were:\nAbout a million consumers said they ex\npected to buy new houses this year, but half\nof them want to pay less than $7,000\u2014the\nmoderate price range in which few houses\nare to be had.\nThe poll confirmed the fact that more\nconsumers are buying on credit. About 65\nper cent of those who bought cars in 1945\nreported paying the full cash price com\npared with approximately 59 per cent last\nyear and about 52 per cent who expect to\npay cash this year.\nMany of the consumers polled qualified\ntheir buying intentions by saying \u2019they\nwould buy only if prices and quality suited\nthem, or would not buy if they became wor\nried about the economic outlook.\n\nVery little publicity has been given to the\noutspoken dental advice given at the annual\nmeeting of the American Academy of\nDental Medicine. The group worked out an\neducational program to destroy public \u201cob\nsession\u201d with the threat of dental decay and\nto educate us, instead, to the need for pro\ntection against gum disease which, says the\nacademy\u2019s president, Dr. George Bruns, is\nresponsible for \u201cover 80 per cent of all teeth\nlost today.\u201d There is a fact to scare anyone\ninto learning how to brush teeth and gums\nproperly\u2014and to forget the exaggerated\nclaims of the toothpaste ads.","height":"20664","width":"14096"}}
